## M and N

Both letters start **8 states** each:

- {#BF0A30}**M**: Maine, Maryland, Massachusetts, Michigan, Minnesota, Mississippi, Missouri, Montana{/}
- {#1A3A6B}**N**: Nebraska, Nevada, New Hampshire, New Jersey, New Mexico, New York, North Carolina, North Dakota{/}

## West Virginia

{#1A3A6B}**Split from Virginia** during the *Civil War* in **1863**.{/}

The only state to begin with **"West"**.

## Montgomery

{#1A3A6B}**Capital of Alabama**{/}

Named after Revolutionary War general Richard Montgomery.

## Juneau

{#1A3A6B}**Capital of Alaska**{/}

The only US state capital *not reachable by road*.

## Phoenix

{#1A3A6B}**Capital of Arizona**{/}

Named after the mythical bird that rises from its own ashes.

## Little Rock

{#1A3A6B}**Capital of Arkansas**{/}

Named for a *small rock* on the Arkansas River.

## Sacramento

{#1A3A6B}**Capital of California**{/}

Founded during the *California Gold Rush*.

## Denver

{#1A3A6B}**Capital of Colorado**{/}

Known as the **Mile High City** — exactly one mile above sea level.

## Hartford

{#1A3A6B}**Capital of Connecticut**{/}

The **Insurance Capital of the World**.

## Dover

{#1A3A6B}**Capital of Delaware**{/}

Home to **Dover Air Force Base**.

## Tallahassee

{#1A3A6B}**Capital of Florida**{/}

From a Muskogean word meaning *"old fields"*.

## Atlanta

{#1A3A6B}**Capital of Georgia**{/}

Nicknamed the **City in a Forest** for its urban tree canopy.

## Honolulu

{#1A3A6B}**Capital of Hawaii**{/}

Meaning *"sheltered harbor"* in Hawaiian.

## Boise

{#1A3A6B}**Capital of Idaho**{/}

Named by French-Canadian fur trappers — *"les bois"* means *the woods*.

## Springfield

{#1A3A6B}**Capital of Illinois**{/}

**Abraham Lincoln's** home for 24 years.

## Indianapolis

{#1A3A6B}**Capital of Indiana**{/}

Home of the **Indianapolis 500**.

## Des Moines

{#1A3A6B}**Capital of Iowa**{/}

From the French *"rivière des Moines"* — *river of the monks*.

## Topeka

{#1A3A6B}**Capital of Kansas**{/}

From a Kansa word meaning *"a good place to dig potatoes"*.

## Frankfort

{#1A3A6B}**Capital of Kentucky**{/}

One of the *smallest* state capitals by population.

## Baton Rouge

{#1A3A6B}**Capital of Louisiana**{/}

French for *"red stick"*.

## Augusta

{#1A3A6B}**Capital of Maine**{/}

Named after the daughter of a Revolutionary War general.

## Annapolis

{#1A3A6B}**Capital of Maryland**{/}

Home to the **US Naval Academy**.

## Boston

{#1A3A6B}**Capital of Massachusetts**{/}

Site of the **Boston Tea Party** — 1773.

## Lansing

{#1A3A6B}**Capital of Michigan**{/}

Named after *Lansing, New York*.

## Saint Paul

{#1A3A6B}**Capital of Minnesota**{/}

Twin city with **Minneapolis**.

## Jackson

{#1A3A6B}**Capital of Mississippi**{/}

Named after **Andrew Jackson**.

## Jefferson City

{#1A3A6B}**Capital of Missouri**{/}

Named after **Thomas Jefferson**.

## Helena

{#1A3A6B}**Capital of Montana**{/}

Founded during the **Montana Gold Rush** of 1864.

## Lincoln

{#1A3A6B}**Capital of Nebraska**{/}

Named after **Abraham Lincoln** — originally called *Lancaster*.

## Carson City

{#1A3A6B}**Capital of Nevada**{/}

Named after frontiersman **Kit Carson**.

## Concord

{#1A3A6B}**Capital of New Hampshire**{/}

Home to the *primary that kicks off each presidential election year*.

## Trenton

{#1A3A6B}**Capital of New Jersey**{/}

Site of **Washington's** famous Christmas 1776 crossing of the Delaware.

## Santa Fe

{#1A3A6B}**Capital of New Mexico**{/}

Founded in *1610* — the **oldest state capital** in the US.

## Albany

{#1A3A6B}**Capital of New York**{/}

One of the **oldest surviving European settlements** in the US.

## Raleigh

{#1A3A6B}**Capital of North Carolina**{/}

Named after **Sir Walter Raleigh**.

## Bismarck

{#1A3A6B}**Capital of North Dakota**{/}

Named after the German Chancellor **Otto von Bismarck**.

## Columbus

{#1A3A6B}**Capital of Ohio**{/}

Named after **Christopher Columbus**.

## Oklahoma City

{#1A3A6B}**Capital of Oklahoma**{/}

The only US state capital that shares its name with its state.

## Salem

{#1A3A6B}**Capital of Oregon**{/}

From the Hebrew *"shalom"* — meaning *peace*.

## Harrisburg

{#1A3A6B}**Capital of Pennsylvania**{/}

Home to **Three Mile Island** nuclear plant.

## Providence

{#1A3A6B}**Capital of Rhode Island**{/}

Founded by **Roger Williams** as a refuge for religious dissenters.

## Columbia

{#1A3A6B}**Capital of South Carolina**{/}

Named after **Christopher Columbus**.

## Pierre

{#1A3A6B}**Capital of South Dakota**{/}

One of the *smallest* state capitals by population — about 14,000.

## Nashville

{#1A3A6B}**Capital of Tennessee**{/}

The **Music City** — home of country music.

## Austin

{#1A3A6B}**Capital of Texas**{/}

Named after **Stephen F. Austin**, the *Father of Texas*.

## Salt Lake City

{#1A3A6B}**Capital of Utah**{/}

Founded by **Mormon pioneers** in 1847.

## Montpelier

{#1A3A6B}**Capital of Vermont**{/}

The *least populous* state capital in the US — about 8,000.

## Richmond

{#1A3A6B}**Capital of Virginia**{/}

Former capital of the **Confederacy** during the Civil War.

## Olympia

{#1A3A6B}**Capital of Washington**{/}

Named after the nearby **Olympic Mountains**.

## Charleston

{#1A3A6B}**Capital of West Virginia**{/}

Located where the **Elk** and **Kanawha** rivers meet.

## Madison

{#1A3A6B}**Capital of Wisconsin**{/}

Named after **James Madison**, the *4th US President*.

## Cheyenne

{#1A3A6B}**Capital of Wyoming**{/}

Named after the **Cheyenne** people.
